```

## Requirements

- Python 3.11+
- Ollama installed locally
- A local model pulled in Ollama, for example:

```bash
ollama pull qwen2.5-coder:7b
```

## Quick Start

From the repo root:

```bash
ollama serve
```

In a second terminal:

```bash
cd Nova
python -m nova_ai.cli ask "Explain the structure of this repo"
```

Or use the launchers:

```bash
./nova ask "Explain the structure of this repo"
./nova --profile python chat
./Nova/run --profile minecraft ask "Explain this mod"
```

Nova responds to plain text prompts like:

```bash
./nova --profile python ask "Help me build an async file watcher"
./nova --profile bash ask "Write a deployment script with rollback checks"
./nova --profile minecraft ask "How should I structure a Fabric networking layer?"
```

To create a starter project inside Nova's own workspace:

```bash
./nova create-project "Potion Helper"
./nova create-project "Server Backup" --template bash-script
./nova create-project "Crystal Tools" --template minecraft-fabric
```

## Credits

Nova now has a simple local credits system.
Each prompt costs `1` credit by default.
State is stored under [Nova/.nova](/workspaces/codespaces-blank/Nova/.nova).

Examples:

```bash
./nova credits status
./nova credits add 25
./nova credits disable
./nova credits enable
./nova credits reset
```

To set an admin bypass password:

```bash
./nova credits set-admin-password
```

To use bypass access:

```bash
./nova --access-password "your-password" --profile python ask "Help me refactor this module"
```

You can also create limited access grants for someone else:

```bash
./nova credits grant-create --name "friend-pass" --prompts 20
./nova credits grant-create --name "trial-pass" --prompts 10 --hours 24
./nova credits grant-list
./nova credits grant-revoke --grant-id abc123ef
```

You can store a password in the environment with:

```bash
export NOVA_ACCESS_PASSWORD="your-password"
```

To point Nova at another repository:

```bash
python -m nova_ai.cli ask "Where is auth implemented?" --repo /path/to/project
```

To override the model:

```bash
python -m nova_ai.cli ask "Suggest a refactor for this file" --model qwen2.5-coder:7b
```

To use a focused profile:

```bash
python -m nova_ai.cli --profile python ask "Help me write a clean CLI tool"
python -m nova_ai.cli --profile bash ask "Write a safe backup script"
python -m nova_ai.cli --profile minecraft ask "Explain this Fabric mod structure"
```

To use a custom knowledge folder:

```bash
./nova --knowledge-dir /path/to/notes --profile python ask "Follow my local coding rules"
```

## Interactive Mode

```bash
python -m nova_ai.cli chat
```

Helpful commands inside chat:

- `/help` show commands
- `/files` list tracked files in the repo
- `/projects` list projects in `NovaProjects`
- `/knowledge` show the active knowledge directory
- `/credits` show the current credit status
- `/read path/to/file.py` print a file
- `/search some_text` search the repo
- `/run pytest -q` run a command with confirmation
- `/repo /path/to/repo` switch repository
- `/model llama3.1:8b` switch model
- `/profile minecraft` switch Nova's domain behavior
- `/quit` exit chat

## Design Notes

Nova is intentionally tool-driven.
The model is responsible for reasoning and drafting.
The local tool layer is responsible for:

- finding context
- reading code safely
- searching the workspace
- collecting command output
- storing patch proposals

The current version does not auto-edit files. It generates patch proposals you can review first.

## Knowledge Files

Nova now reads markdown knowledge files before answering:

- [knowledge/common.md](/workspaces/codespaces-blank/Nova/knowledge/common.md) — core coding practices
- [knowledge/python.md](/workspaces/codespaces-blank/Nova/knowledge/python.md) — Python fundamentals
- [knowledge/python_advanced.md](/workspaces/codespaces-blank/Nova/knowledge/python_advanced.md) — async, concurrency, packaging, architecture
- [knowledge/bash.md](/workspaces/codespaces-blank/Nova/knowledge/bash.md) — Bash safety and portability
- [knowledge/bash_advanced.md](/workspaces/codespaces-blank/Nova/knowledge/bash_advanced.md) — advanced script structure, system automation, debugging
- [knowledge/minecraft.md](/workspaces/codespaces-blank/Nova/knowledge/minecraft.md) — mod/plugin platform detection
- [knowledge/minecraft_advanced.md](/workspaces/codespaces-blank/Nova/knowledge/minecraft_advanced.md) — Fabric/Forge threading, mixins, rendering, registries

This is the easiest way to teach Nova your preferences without retraining a model.
You can write things like:

- preferred commands
- project structure notes
- coding standards
- common mistakes to watch for
- Minecraft platform/version notes

Nova also now has a dedicated project workspace at [NovaProjects](/workspaces/codespaces-blank/NovaProjects), so new starter projects can live there instead of being mixed into other repos.

## VS Code Side Panel

Nova can now run as a VS Code extension side panel.

To set up:

1. Open the `Nova/vscode-nova` folder in VS Code.
2. Run `Developer: Reload Window` (or press F5 to start debugging the extension).
3. Open the command palette and select `Nova: Open Side Panel`.
4. Type your prompt and click `Ask Nova`.

See [vscode-nova/README.md](/workspaces/codespaces-blank/Nova/vscode-nova/README.md) for more details.

## How To Teach It Better Over Time

For Python:

- keep a few strong local example repos
- ask for traceback analysis, refactors, tests, and docstrings
- prefer prompts that mention files, errors, and expected behavior
- add Python architecture, concurrency, and optimization examples to [knowledge/python_advanced.md](/workspaces/codespaces-blank/Nova/knowledge/python_advanced.md)

For Bash:

- keep shell scripts in one folder so Nova can inspect patterns
- ask it to explain quoting and failure modes
- test scripts with small commands first
- add script structure, automation, and debugging patterns to [knowledge/bash_advanced.md](/workspaces/codespaces-blank/Nova/knowledge/bash_advanced.md)

For Minecraft coding:

- point Nova at the actual mod/plugin repo
- mention whether you are building Fabric, Forge, Paper, Spigot, or datapacks
- include Minecraft version in your prompt when it matters
- keep build files and mod metadata files present so Nova can infer the stack
- add platform-specific patterns, registry techniques, and threading models to [knowledge/minecraft_advanced.md](/workspaces/codespaces-blank/Nova/knowledge/minecraft_advanced.md)

If you eventually want deeper specialization, the next upgrade is to add a local knowledge folder with:

- style guides
- example snippets
- common commands
- project conventions
- troubleshooting notes

